Last fall, it seemed that the expectation was that OPEC would announce some changes because of pressure from member states (Venezuela, Nigeria, Russia, Libya) due to the fall in oil prices.  Instead, Saudi Arabia, more concerned about maintaining its market-share than the price, prevailed and no changes were made.   What are the arguments against any change this fall?  
1)  OPEC doesn't control the market anymore.  A production cut is unlikely to have a dramatic impact on the price;  
2) most OPEC countries exceed their quotas anyway so what would be the point?  why open that can of worms?;  
3) production remains high to protect market share, and some revenue is preferable to  none; 
4) The Saudis continue to care more about market share than price; 
5)  the low price is working to preserve OPEC market share in the broader energy market.  It is driving some oil out of the market and reducing exploration & development of new sources.  High cost exploration & develop in the Arctic in Alaska & Russia  has been dramatically cut back in the last year.  All alternative energy sources (solar, wind, etc) become less viable when oil is cheap, so low priced oil slows R & D in alternative energy and stretches out the dominance of oil in the energy sector. What's changed in the last year and/or is on the horizon for the next 12 months?  
1)  Just about every oil producer is in worse economic/financial shape than last year so wants to pump more or do something to increase the price; 
2) Iran will re-enter the market, won't some change need to be made to accommodate that?; 
3) Indonnesia is expected to rejoin OPEC:  won't that necessitate a change in quota?
4) there's a new Saudi King, a man who, prior to becoming king, was described as not totally compos mentis.  Does he have the respect, clout or vision to continue to dominate OPEC?
5) Venezuela's leader Maduro's economic policies have been recognized as a major source of Venezuela's problems so OPEC members may not have much sympathy for Venezuela's problems or pleas. What hasn't changed?
1)  Saudi Arabia seems to still be more concerned about market share than price and has the financial reserves to weather the low price storm.  It is giving no signals that it is considering a change
2)  global production is still exceeding demand
3) since OPEC countries routinely exceed the quota, what would be the point of changing it?
4) since the quota isn't by country, there's no need to adjust it for the entry of Indonnesia and increased production by Iran Last fall, I thought that the human and political need to "do something" to fix the low oil prices would lead to a change in quota; I was wrong.  Perhaps I've been wrong about it again; the crowd says 20% no.  So, I'm coming down to 50%.  The only reason I'm not going lower at this time is because the question asks about "ANY" changes, which means there's an infinite number of ways that this question could resolve as "Yes".
